Great question. Java has **3 main variants** of ThreadLocal.

---

## 1. `ThreadLocal` — Standard
The basic one. Each thread gets its own independent copy.

```java
ThreadLocal<String> local = new ThreadLocal<>();
local.set("hello");
local.get(); // → "hello" only in this thread
```
Use when: each thread needs **completely isolated** state.

---

## 2. `InheritableThreadLocal` — Parent to Child Inheritance
When a child thread is spawned, it **inherits a copy** of the parent's value at the time of creation.

```java
InheritableThreadLocal<String> local = new InheritableThreadLocal<>();
local.set("parent-value");

Thread child = new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println(local.get()); // → "parent-value"
    local.set("child-value");        // only changes child's copy
    System.out.println(local.get()); // → "child-value"
});
child.start();

System.out.println(local.get()); // → "parent-value" (parent unaffected)
```

**Gotcha:** Value is copied **at thread creation time**, not dynamically. If parent changes value after spawning, child won't see it.

Use when: passing request context (user, traceId) from parent to child threads.

---

## 3. `TransmittableThreadLocal` (TTL) — Thread Pool Safe Inheritance
A library (`com.alibaba:transmittable-thread-local`) that solves the biggest gap — `InheritableThreadLocal` **breaks with thread pools** because threads are reused, not freshly spawned.

```xml
<!-- pom.xml -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.alibaba</groupId>
    <artifactId>transmittable-thread-local</artifactId>
    <version>2.14.3</version>
</dependency>
```

```java
TransmittableThreadLocal<String> local = new TransmittableThreadLocal<>();
local.set("request-123");

ExecutorService executor = TtlExecutors.getTtlExecutorService(
    Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5) // wrap your executor
);

executor.submit(() -> {
    System.out.println(local.get()); // → "request-123" ✅
});
```

Without TTL, a pooled thread would return `null` or worse, a **previous request's value**.

Use when: propagating traceId, user context across thread pools in **microservices or async tasks**.

---

## Side by Side Comparison

| | `ThreadLocal` | `InheritableThreadLocal` | `TransmittableThreadLocal` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Isolated per thread | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Child inherits parent value | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Works with thread pools | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Built into JDK | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ (3rd party) |
| Use case | Per-thread state | Spawned threads | Async / pooled tasks |

---

## Bonus — `ThreadLocal` with `withInitial`
Not a separate type, but a cleaner way to define a default value lazily:

```java
// Instead of this:
ThreadLocal<List<String>> local = new ThreadLocal<>();
if (local.get() == null) local.set(new ArrayList<>());

// Do this:
ThreadLocal<List<String>> local = ThreadLocal.withInitial(ArrayList::new);
// auto-initializes on first get() per thread
```

---

**Which one should you use?**

- Plain app with no async → **`ThreadLocal`**
- Spawning raw threads and need context passed down → **`InheritableThreadLocal`**
- Thread pools, Spring async, CompletableFuture → **`TransmittableThreadLocal`**
